Welcome to March's Turing-Roche newsletter! Here you can find what's new in the Turing-Roche strategic partnership and opportunities, events and news from both The Alan Turing Institute, Roche and the wider community.

Our [five year partnership](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F8I9FEh4JUktU_239UQe9Uw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=tgElCOE%2BwI7NPCP5oN7CqVEIPZcvmebxQpKwCSi8jt8%3D&reserved=0) was set up officially in June 2021 following a successful [Data Study Group](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F2PFu2YwUITambZrONKP_iQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=5W2VUL0jlhYkt885L%2BSit2ZkX0tnZC3iL9V8qc1flA4%3D&reserved=0) and a 12 week research project on lung cancer treatment. Our 'North Star' is **to enable the generation of insights to better understand patient and disease heterogeneity and its relevance to clinical outcomes at an unprecedented level of precision in order to improve clinical care.**

We will be covering multiple activities over the five years to work towards our North Star, as well as building strong connections and collaborations between the Alan Turing Institute, Roche and the wider community.

If you have anything you'd like featured in a future newsletter then please get in touch with Vicky Hellon, Community Manager for the partnership at <vhellon@turing.ac.uk>

If you would like to share this newsletter with relevant colleagues please direct them to sign-up [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FMAZoQwnXwZqYhmQkFZ13Wg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=oW02MLI%2Bmmqt6KkpMx3%2FevWef8W%2F0OSxV240iMfF6rQ%3D&reserved=0).

### Partnership funds project for Predictive Modelling Research Theme

Following on from our [Structured Missingness funded projects](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F1qLxO0CmLLsaG1zZ1kxRQg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=yXkWJG252hDx9oJh1Kb%2BVppa7zUoTrZWnJquq0IsYyQ%3D&reserved=0), we're delighted to have now funded an 18-month project for our second research theme- Predictive Modelling in the context of uncertainty and heterogeneity in biomedical data.

Dr Brieuc Lehmann and his co-researchers Professor Karla Diaz-Ordaz (University College London), Professor Ricardo Silva (University College London) and Dr Matthew Sperrin (University of Manchester) will explore statistical and machine learning methods to measure and minimise biases and unfairness in clinical prediction models. Find out more [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FkpFRs5glEmqM-1zJ9Wygug&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Asbx9Qf7X6IRrjT1Ow4Wjutwhu0%2F1%2BL1oe2vqQ%2BqtKA%3D&reserved=0). The project team are also hiring a postdoctoral researcher for the project (application deadline 21st March) - you can find out more at the [job ad](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPThuaGZhSzFJWG96TWRzeHpGTnhZdUgtZl9OZmI1a0RoZl9Td2NkQVNXZGZxUVYwZHdObW5CNkVLalY5Qm1ZNlImcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi0xNTQ1NDg4NzY1ZTA0NjQ0ODRkZGI0YTI1NzBhOTc1YSZlc2lkPWY3M2NlZTFjLTZhYmUtZWQxMS04M2ZlLTAwMjI0ODA3MDcyMyJ9%2F4rBL2vWhrDTG15HHjrA6Sg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=x%2B4OG5cVyUkAit6lK4H7BXYCunH4jAB0Hq2ue2n7Z1o%3D&reserved=0).

### Knowledge Share Series Event: Explainable AI in Health

**28 March 2023**

Join us for our [partnership knowledge share series](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FCsPoYVxza2lwV3d11AYVhg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=nMuOypQSbJN%2Bif21GMHYIU68XCCYUzPQTVl%2FhKDbGy4%3D&reserved=0). Our aim is to bring together members of the Turing and Roche networks and the wider scientific community to share different academic and industry perspectives on areas related to patient/treatment heterogeneity and data science more generally.

March's event is on the 28th and this month our theme will be Explainable AI in Health. We'll be exploring how we ensure AI-assisted decisions, methods and tools are transparent and clear to all involved, which is becoming particularly crucial in the health sphere.

We will be hearing from Ali Boushehri, a PhD Student in Computational Biology at Roche and Antonella Maia Perini, a Research Associate in the Public Policy Programme at the Turing Institute.You can register for the event [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fz_QInEnexQmz5MghH7uoYQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=%2F4Tm0cflBtf5I7Yot7%2BFDJYvHQKdNevyPl9jcvrg3cc%3D&reserved=0).

You can catch-up on previous recordings of our events at our [YouTube channel](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FN1oSgeM8-jVjsenw6Vok1Q&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=aQDWre0xZ80aQU29xPmleK4Xbq7OE5YAlkMEEbYRIKg%3D&reserved=0). ### Partnership Team Member James Jackson visits Parliament!

![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/jamesjacksonstemforbritain6bdf.jpeg)

James Jackson, our Postdoctoral Research Associate for our Structured Missingness Research Theme, took part in [STEM for Britain](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPThuaGZhSzFJWG96TWRzeHpGTnhZdUgtZl9OZmI1a0RoZl9Td2NkQVNXZGZxUVYwZHdObW5CNkVLalY5Qm1ZNlImcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi0xNTQ1NDg4NzY1ZTA0NjQ0ODRkZGI0YTI1NzBhOTc1YSZlc2lkPWY3M2NlZTFjLTZhYmUtZWQxMS04M2ZlLTAwMjI0ODA3MDcyMyJ9%2F026SOfS6rgNeopK77o7OEg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=zb0lwUFUCeoj1amtUXso0E%2Fn8%2BQjuWqn56Vcvhv7KkA%3D&reserved=0) on Monday 6th March. STEM for Britain is a major scientific poster competition and exhibition which has been held in Parliament since 1997, and is organised by the Parliamentary & Scientific Committee. Chaired by Stephen Metcalfe MP, its aim is to give members of both Houses of Parliament an insight into the outstanding research work being undertaken in UK universities by early-career researchers.

James was presenting a poster on his PhD work on Synthetic Data. He had a great experience and mentioned that its an annual event, so would encourage any interested early or mid career researchers to apply for next time!

### Turing Institute Data Study Group- May

**Deadline for applications: 27 March 2023**

**Data Study Group event: 15-26 May 2023**

Turing Data Study Groups are intensive five-day collaborative, sprint-style research activities which bring together organisations from industry, government, and the third sector, with talented multi-disciplinary researchers from academia. Organisations act as Challenge Owners, providing real-world problems to be tackled by researchers. The events provide a fantastic opportunity for early career researchers to rapidly develop their data science skills using real-world data.

May's Data Study Group will be hosted at the Turing Institute with challenges from:

- Dstl -- Using topic modeling to find emerging topics & trends in academic papers\
- Environmental Investigation Agency -- Identifying Tiger Stripe Patterns\
- Johnson Matthey -- Increasing Automation Using Machine Learning Methods\
- NBN Trust -- Spatiotemporal analysis of species in the UK using the largest publicly accessible source of biodiversity data\
- Peak District National Park Authority -- Using multi-spectral remotely sensed imagery to improve land cover classification

Find out more information and how to apply [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fo1IiH5JV7Xk-Jv0nBYkvfw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=DznAXwG0ocbYBNn0MgB13MyVsBXg7%2BIJ3bcif4A1vqA%3D&reserved=0).

### Opening up Roche (OUR) Internship Opportunity for 2023

**Deadline for applications: 31 March 2023**

Opening Up Roche (OUR) is a programme designed to introduce young talent to Roche. It deliberately seeks applicants who, for whatever reason, might not see Roche as a natural destination- specifically welcoming students with underrepresented backgrounds to apply. The Internship is for 3 months, either full time or part time, starting in June / July and finishing September / October, based out of Welwyn (UK), Basel (Switzerland) or Penzberg, Mannheim (Germany). The internships are sponsored by a wide range of Roche departments including Manufacturing, Pharma technical development, Quality, Regulatory and Supply Chain. More info and how to apply [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Foec1jF6NkdfS6UsCYraGYw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=0O8ecrEjTKLIb%2BWGLAapZxrnmcK%2Bchanf%2BkhDM9I69k%3D&reserved=0).

### Turing Institute Theory and Methods Challenge Fortnights in Data Science and AI 2023

**Deadline for applications: 24 March 2023**

The Theory and Methods Challenge Fortnights (TMCF) bring together experts from the Turing University Network and other institutions worldwide to join forces for a multi-day research event on a specific theoretical or methodological challenge.

Applications are now open to propose a challenge which can be can be drawn from any discipline in the data science and AI ecosystems. Researchers not formally affiliated with The Alan Turing Institute can submit proposals, as long as they have a Turing affiliate as a Co-I. Successful proposals will receive sufficient funding to fully cover travel, subsistence, and accommodation (and reasonable caring responsibility costs, as necessary) for the challenge team (up to 12 people including international attendees) for a maximum of 2 weeks. More and how to apply [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FZWsyygIZrD_bq_MAlHgZxQ&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=GQbbJdFAiHZEDLT2ld4irPrYLyYWqsNnXj92XyO3JkA%3D&reserved=0).

### New Alan Turing Online Learning Platform

The Turing Institute have launched a new online learning platform, which offers free, open source courses for researchers and professionals in data science or AI fields. The platform provides the opportunity to learn new skills, enhance your knowledge, and apply best practice in topics including Fairness and Responsibility in Human-AI interaction in medical settings, Assessing and Mitigating Bias and Discrimination in AI, Data Visualisation and more. With expert instructors and hands-on activities, courses are designed with real-world applications in mind. You can find the platform [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPThuaGZhSzFJWG96TWRzeHpGTnhZdUgtZl9OZmI1a0RoZl9Td2NkQVNXZGZxUVYwZHdObW5CNkVLalY5Qm1ZNlImcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi0xNTQ1NDg4NzY1ZTA0NjQ0ODRkZGI0YTI1NzBhOTc1YSZlc2lkPWY3M2NlZTFjLTZhYmUtZWQxMS04M2ZlLTAwMjI0ODA3MDcyMyJ9%2F6CjNVmhDZzpjDLnIkpPusA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361607239%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=HGe0braIwg3LDFpYxJ%2FbXzr1h6XM8dcCvQT5xAuq97w%3D&reserved=0).\

### AI for multiple long-term conditions Research Support Facility (AIM RSF) Seminar: Structured missing data: Grand challenges in learning from multi-modal data at scale

**14 March 2023**

## Publication of the Month

![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/patrick-tomasso-oaqk7qqnh_c-unsplash2.jpg)

### User-centred design for machine learning in health care: a case study from care management

March's publication of the month is this [paper](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fv4IjgCLTkYYE3KrqCc8cRg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7C8787415110434fec51d408db23b29f02%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638143022361763508%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=RoDG7AnLSLhycWDcFsrMavE8F05VQ3AJmdeErx0DZdc%3D&reserved=0) from researchers at Stanford University and Google, published in BMJ Health and Care Informatics. Relevant to research our partnership team are currently exploring around fairness, the paper introduces a pratical toolkit for integrating users (in this case stakeholders delivering care) in the machine learning life cycle, aiming to improve the configuration of models so they can be more successfully deployed in clinical practice.
